The main contributions and features of this research are as follows.

                           •

Presenting a mathematical model emphasizing the significance of both collective and individual living conditions that emerge amid pandemics;


                           •

Analyzing the control measures-induced short-term negative effects for weakening the COVID-19 transmission chain on the socioeconomic and environmental dimensions of human life considering the SDGs and sustainability approach;


                           •

Considering the rate of domestic violence and suicide as the indications of social factors, the rate of food inflation as the representative of economic and social factors, and the unemployment rate representing economic, social, and environmental factors in the proposed model;


                           •

Selecting an optimal option between manufacturing domestic vaccines, purchasing foreign vaccines, or a combination of these two for supplying and distributing the vaccines within the shortest time period;


                           •

Presenting an effective solution in order to come up with herd immunity pursuing the goal of optimizing cost, utility, and negative outcomes of the control measures for reducing the prevalence of COVID-19;


                           •

Selecting Iran as a case study and solving the model to evaluate it in a large size, and analyzing the sensitivity of the model.
